    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my tomato plants are looking kind of sickly. the leaves on the bottom are turning yellow and falling off. what do you think is going on?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your tomato plants are likely suffering from a classic case of **old leaf senescence**, which is a natural process where the plant recycles nutrients from the bottom leaves to fuel the fruiting and growth of the new top leaves. However, if the yellowing is accompanied by wilting or spots, it could be a sign of **root rot** or **nutrient deficiency**, which is a bit more concerning.\n\nTo help your plants recover, you should **prune off the yellowed lower leaves** to improve air circulation and reduce the risk of fungal infections, but be careful not to remove too many at once, as this can stress the plant. Additionally, ensure your soil is well-draining and that you are watering at the base of the plant rather than overhead, to prevent fungal issues. If the leaves are turning yellow very quickly or the plant looks droopy, it might be a sign of **overwatering** or **pest infestation**, so you should check the soil moisture and inspect the undersides of the leaves for bugs.\n\nIn the meantime, you might want to consider adding some **compost** or **balanced fertilizer** to replenish any depleted nutrients, but avoid over-fertilizing, as this can burn",
      "source": "target",
