    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a perfect analogy! It's like the nutrients are hiding in a vault, and the plant is too weak to pick the lock because the acid is too high. To make sure nothing else is stripping the soil bare, you need to be vigilant against **leaching** and **erosion**, which are the two main ways a hungry plant loses its treasure.\n\nFirst, **leaching** happens when you water too heavily or too frequently, washing the nutrients right out of the root zone into the groundwater. It's like pouring a bucket of water over a treasure chest and watching the gold sink to the bottom of the ocean. To stop this, try **drip irrigation** or watering deeply but less often so the water soaks in and brings the nutrients back up to the roots. Also, make sure your soil has enough **organic matter** like compost; think of it as a thick, sticky blanket that holds the nutrients in place so they don't wash away.\n\nSecond, **erosion** can happen if the wind or rain blows the top layer of soil away, taking the nutrients with it. This is especially bad if you don't have mulch. You should cover the base of your tomato plants with **straw,",
